{#- DEFINITION → prose, sand alt -#}
<section class="sec reveal hub-rt--alt" id="switch-from-pilot-definition" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">In plain terms</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:14px;">What switching from Pilot means, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Switching from Pilot means taking your bookkeeping off Pilot&rsquo;s managed service and putting it onto your own QuickBooks company file &mdash; a file you own and control &mdash; maintained going forward by a single named Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor. Your historical financials and transactions are brought across, the opening balances are set correctly, every account is reconciled so it ties to the bank, and from there a ProAdvisor runs your monthly close on a set cadence.</p>
      <p>It&rsquo;s worth being fair about who Pilot is for. Pilot is a reputable, operating bookkeeping and finance service built around venture-backed startups &mdash; accrual-first, oriented to fundraising and audit readiness &mdash; and for many funded companies that&rsquo;s exactly the right model. This page isn&rsquo;t an argument that Pilot is wrong; it&rsquo;s a path for businesses whose needs have moved on: those who want a portable, CPA-ready file of their own, a named person instead of a team queue, a cost that matches a non-VC profile, or simply a fit beyond the startup mold. If you&rsquo;re still deciding whether to move at all, the <a href="/vs/techbrot-vs-pilot/">comparison page</a> lays out both sides; this page is for when the decision is made.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

